Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, they have 29 percent in total
According to the preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current grand coalition, as well as a notorious strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (<0xC3><0x96>VP), where the position of the current president Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly heavy losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZ<0xC3><0x96>), the governor of Carinthia Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at the national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SP<0xC3><0x96>) remain, with 29.8 percent of the vote, the country's leading political force, however, compared to the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
The <0xC3><0x96>VP, which with 25.6 percent loses nearly nine percent of the vote, ended up even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major post-war parties; especially for the popular party, which triggered the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Still in early July, when the <0xC3><0x96>VP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SP<0xC3><0x96>.
Now, voters visibly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculations were made about the possible resignation of the party leader and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday, at the party’s extraordinary leadership council.
Such an evolution would a priori facilitate the path towards the outcome of the election result which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the grand coalition SP<0xC3><0x96> and <0xC3><0x96>VP.
Nevertheless, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free (FP<0xC3><0x96>) would have obtained 18 percent and the BZ<0xC3><0x96> eleven percent of the vote - the Socialists expressed at the same time the fear of a repetition of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FP<0xC3><0x96> was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZ<0xC3><0x96> split from the common government).
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he plans to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently bets on this evolution.
The last party to have access to parliament was the Greens, but they slightly lost and fell, among Austrian political parties, from third to fifth.
Clearly, no other party crossed the four-percent limit and entered parliament.
