A Czech arbitrates the fight for the seabed
It approaches a walled electronic map, on which Australia and adjacent marine areas are depicted.
But he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
This area is however as large as the continent itself," says Italian jurist Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the team of 30 members of the UN Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea.
Its head, the director of the division, the Czech jurist V<0xC3><0xA1>clav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
The ardor at work and the enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a world little known so far, rich in natural resources.
There are oil, minerals and other mineral resources, but also living organisms that are currently unknown, which may hold the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A bottom wider than the land
The coastal states have now begun to aspire vehemently to the new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they use their rights, which they agreed to in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of what is known as the continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter may, according to the Convention, exclusively claim all the resources of the continental shelf.
"To simplify, continental shelf is considered the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which constitutes a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the boundaries of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic zone,” Mikulka said.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf, must be supported by a broad scientific and technical documentation, based on many expensive surveys and metrical data.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the committee has dealt with five requests, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia, which is the first to significantly expand its underwater possessions, has recently had a global impact.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which the commission assigned to it last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometers, which represents the extent of the country multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The benefit they will derive in the future from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they project, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their request.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the Montego Bay Convention.
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no state has an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"However, let's not be mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," director Mikulka said, exaggerating, noting that "its areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime is anchored in a contract."
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed now also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern bloc countries within the framework of the common organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, under the Convention, the Commission, as well as investors from a few other States, obtained the status of the so-called "pioneer investor".
It has the right of extraction in the Clarion Clipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The background is enlivened, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatras.
"It is possible to extract on an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area represents a deposit rich in polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," said Ind Pakshi Rajan, another jurist.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, brings an example of such a realization.
It recalls a small potato, or, with a little imagination, the mythical shoe, which, according to legend, animated the Golem.
