Organizers report an increasing number of bookings
This should be a good winter for German travel agencies:
In terms of bookings for the coming months, according to a study, the turnover has increased significantly compared to the previous year - for the winter season, even more than 30 percent.
Despite weak economic prospects, the Germans’ thirst for travel remains insatiable, according to this study.
In terms of bookings for the winter season, travel agencies recorded revenues of more than 31 percent compared to the same period the previous year, as the German Federation of Travel Agencies (DRV) told Berlin on Monday.
According to a survey by the GfK Market Research Institute, growing booking numbers are already dominating the autumn months.
Thus the sales figure would have risen to about 11 percent more compared to 2007, the DRV said.
The sources of these results are the figures of the GfK, which analyses monthly booking data from 1,200 travel agencies and makes estimates for the global market.
Travel bookings made since the end of August 2008 would be recorded there.
Due to the low price of the dollar, travel to the USA would be particularly in demand, said DRV.
There, the increase in bookings would amount to about a third.
Besides that, Spain, Turkey and Greece as well as our country would be destinations particularly sought after by the Germans.
Organized trips in particular are in high demand, explained DRV President Klaus Laepple.
In view of the rising prices of energy and food products, the costs here would be "more easily calculable for the customer than for an individually organized trip".
Consumers can save money among other things with early booking discounts or All Inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months have also been very tight, so that an increase in sales figures will again be recorded compared to last year - although according to another study, the number of Germans who have undertaken a trip has decreased compared to the previous year.
