The ‘bee car’ that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has taken inspiration, this time, from nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the theft of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have designed the small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Chief Public Relations Officer for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan Safety Shield.
This robot will allow the brand’s vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape that closely resembles the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important is the eyes composed of the bee, able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows him to fly without interruption inside his own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed a so-called laser range finder.
It detects obstacles over a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by bifurcating its wheels by 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Displacement Laboratory and principal engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
“Every second this device only has to process information and act on that data.
It does not need to keep the information or the intuitive logic of previous manoeuvres, which is why it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes.”
This represents the first car to develop new technologies for instantaneous collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced in production cars in a decade after Nissan.
The robot runs on lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles on the road.
