A week after unveiling an interim deal, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a unit price of $25.25, or a total amount of $3 billion.
The price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities with a return of 10% and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall deal would be based on an average unit price of $29, or 28 percent above its current price.
Morgan Stanley was down 6.79% at $23.07 around 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to the status of a banking holding company,” said John Mack, CEO of Morgan Stanley.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to diversify its activities but puts it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to take a far more cautious stance than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been modified in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, explained to Tokyo, “we thought that the participation would be entirely composed of ordinary shares.
But given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley shares 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into common shares in a year if they trade more than 50% above the conversion price, or at about $47, during a given period.
Morgan Stanley says MUFG’s capital will allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group, however, declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to have a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" eased its balance sheet since late August.
The past few weeks have been trying for the group, which has seen its stock price melt in half as the cost of insurance against a default risk on its debt soared.
The cost fell back on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of major Wall Street investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the buyout of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refounding the Republic around 21st Century Socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, was the third to put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" received 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a wide victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The "Constitution triumphed in an overwhelming way," he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place quietly according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observer mission, was about a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" advocated by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, reserving it the "development planning" of a country living essentially from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and foreign currencies sent by its emigrants.
Carried by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the head of state, who will be able to carry out up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million people, where 50 per cent of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
All 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault against the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
The apparently fit hostages arrived at around 3.30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft at the al-Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, unable to speak to the press, in helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health," and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been swept from one hideout to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptus, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, carrying two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," the official, who requested anonymity, said.
He said a total of 150 Egyptian special forces members of the "lightning" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our secret service men, special forces," he said, without further detail.
He also denied the payment of ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and occupies this election campaign.
Good for you.
But one part of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the sums of misery that are given to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historic sites that are starving?
What politician will dare remind the federal government that he neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government spends three and a half million euros on the restoration of the only Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
Among our American neighbors, it is written in the Constitution of their country that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and this in concert.
In Quebec, at the Fédération des sociétés d'histoire du Québec, at least 40,000 volunteers in 211 history, heritage, archival and genealogical societies are concerned with digging through history, preserving private archives with three subsets, and preserving archaeological remains.
They are often the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when promoters and decision-makers throw their bulldozers at our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When, a forum for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European bank in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries support, up to a sum of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also having interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, in this case, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s Competition Officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the amplifying international financial crisis in more than a year is for Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy almost half (up to 49%) of the capital of the bank located in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its holdings, including, in the first place, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares began a dizzying fall, and in the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday, the company’s shares fell 12 percent to their lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group’s capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company’s executives, is not realistic.
The company's management accuses the overseas uncertainty, related to the adoption of the US $700 billion bailout, of being the cause of the fall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank’s customer circle and no agency was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also bought out leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become out of control.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information about the prescription of medicines, in any case, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it amounts to entrusting your chicken coop to a fox," Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told The Washington Post.
The insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage dependent on the health status of the client who presents himself, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they would send candidates for a medical examination, and they would not sign an insurance contract with them until they had heard of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he can easily obtain from pharmacies data on the person's drug purchases in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, which disease the person suffers from and what his state of health is.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol lowering, it refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is not much left to do to the insurer other than paperwork. However, tiny problems may still appear.
Disadvantages of this program include the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while others do not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data. They must seek the patient's permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are compelled to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory analyses, and linking them with data on drug use, thus providing an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time usage control is becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to broaden the circle of control of the authorities over companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not sufficient and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
So, in the end, the hens depend on the fox's kindness.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India double their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside the other, largely global, problems.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be the main issue.
The European Union recognizes that India is an emerging major democratic power that should be given wider voice in international affairs, but member countries have yet to agree on their support in New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue, yesterday, at the 9th summit held in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the head of diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they would double trade, which means an increase of a good hundred euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods increased from $25 billion to $55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious goal.
In this sense, they have harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil flights from a legal point of view, so that air trade can also take off in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's main trading partner, and New Delhi, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan was strongly condemned, as were all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on the subject was raised.
Completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains faithful to the energy and climate programme, including that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20 per cent until 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the fact that a global market should be passed at next year’s climate conference, and greenhouse gas emissions should be reduced by fifty percent until 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported convening an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state travels today to the French capital, where during a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the news agency, the deal would last for 15 years.
In Frankfurt, more than three hundred Italian publishers
A strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than three hundred Italian publishers present at the 60th edition of the Buchmesse, the most important international event in the exchange of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair is waiting for this edition, more than 7 miles of exhibitors from 101 different countries that will occupy the 171,790 square meters of the Fair with more than 403 thousand titles on display, and Turkey as guest of honor.
It will be the Undersecretary of the Ministry of Cultural Property and Activities, Francesco Maria Giro, who will represent the Italian Government, during the inauguration ceremony of the Italian Butterfly: in fact, Italy will be present in an institutional way, with a Point Italy- 264 square meters of exhibition space.
It will be followed by a press meeting in the Room Struktur, at the Buchmesse butterfly 5.0: an opportunity to present the figures, trends and prospects on the position of publishing in Italy.
According to the data, the importance of foreign author books gradually decreases in relation to the total Italian production, and in particular, in relation to that for adults and children.
Found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fosset, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: “The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it was the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared.”
The sheriff said no human remains were found on or around the plane.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) said that a few hours after the wreck was spotted, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft as the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, again in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset’s personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name of Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's research was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history through a long series of records.
On the sixth attempt, he became in 2002, the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had traveled the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters in height, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the publicity you don't expect.
